r, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>decke</i> ‘covering’, a word which was normally used to refer to roofs, but sometimes also to other sorts of covering; modern German <i>Decke</i> still has the twin senses ‘ceiling’ and ‘blanket’.","Dutch: variant of   Dekker  , cognate with 1 above. Compare   De Decker  .","English (London): variant of   Dicker  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dekker","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Dirk, Gerrit, Maurits, Egbert, Gerben, Hendrik, Henk, Martinus, Wim.","Dutch: occupational name for a roofer (a thatcher, slater, shingler, or tiler), Middle Dutch <i>deck(e)re</i>, an agent derivative of <i>decken</i> ‘to cover’.","English: variant of   Dicker  ."]},{"name":"De Decker","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Willem.","Dutch: variant of   Decker  , with the addition of the definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’."]},{"name":"Deckman","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Deckmann</b>: variant of   Decker   1."]},{"name":"Deka","meanings":["Polish: nickname or occupational name from Old Polish <i>deka</i> ‘pillow’ (from Middle High German <i>decke</i>) or from a word meaning ‘dagger, dirk’. Alternatively, it may be an adaptation of German   Decker   or   Deck  .","Indian (Assam): from the Ahom military rank <i>deka</i> ‘four thousand’, referring to the four thousand troops commanded by such an officer. Compare   Barua  ."]},{"name":"Deckert","meanings":["German:","variant of   Decker   1.","from an old personal name, <i>Tagahard</i>, composed of Old High German <i>tac</i> ‘day’ + <i>hart</i> ‘strong’."]},{"name":"Deck","meanings":["South German: metonymic occupational name for a roofer, from Middle High German <i>decke</i> ‘covering, roof’. Compare the later form   Decker  .","Dutch and North German: from the personal name <i>Deck</i>, a local pet form of Dutch <b>Diederik</b> (see   Dederick  ) or German   Dietrich  ."]}]},{"name":"Nelson","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which originated in the Middle Ages as either a patronymic from   Neil   or a metronymic from   Nell .  Use as a given name probably began as a tribute to the British admiral  Lord Nelson  (  1758–1805 ), the victor of the Battle of Trafalgar;  see also  Horatio .  It is, however, now much more common in the United States than in Britain, its popularity there in the 1930s and 40s no doubt having been influenced by the American film actor and singer  Nelson Eddy  (  1901–67 ). Nowadays the name is universally associated with the South African statesman  Nelson Mandela  (  b. 1918 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nelson Decker was born in 1423, in Syleham, Suffolk, England, his father, Mr Decker, was 23 and his mother, Mrs Decker, was 23. He married Hannah Harris in 1445, in Syleham, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died after 1452."},"et":{"1423–after 1452":"1423–pärast 1452","1423–1452":"1423–1452","1425–1452":"1425–1452","1453–1470":"1453–1470","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1425":"1425","1423":"1423","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1452":"1452","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","after 1452":"pärast 1452","England":"England","Syleham, Suffolk, England":"Syleham, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1423–after 1452":"1423–1452 jälkeen","1423–1452":"1423–1452","1425–1452":"1425–1452","1453–1470":"1453–1470","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1425":"1425","1423":"1423","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1452":"1452","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","after 1452":"1452 jälkeen","England":"England","Syleham, Suffolk, England":"Syleham, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1423–after 1452":"1423–après 1452","1423–1452":"1423–1452","1425–1452":"1425–1452","1453–1470":"1453–1470","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1425":"1425","1423":"1423","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1452":"1452","1450":"1450","1470":"1470","after 1452":"après 1452","England":"Angleterre","Syle